rofessor persona\" and frame answers in conversational blocks.However, because your target audience consists of students preparing for an incredibly unforgiving competitive exam (IIT-JEE Advanced), DPO or ORPO (Odds Ratio Preference Optimization) is highly recommended as a final calibration step. SFT models often suffer from three specific flaws that preference alignment fixes:\n1. Mathematical Hallucinations: Spitting out intermediate calculation errors or minor sign drops (e.g., getting the logic right but concluding $+2$ instead of $-2$).\n2. Persona Slippage: Falling back to giving a direct, unhelpful answer key when a problem gets too algebraically complex.\n3. Broken $\\text{\\LaTeX}$ Rendering: Outputting unclosed math symbols like $$ which can ruin a student's front-end experience.\n# Step 1: Create a Preference Alignment Dataset\nTo run preference optimization, you need a dataset structured as triplet sets: a prompt, a chosen response (ideal tutor response), and a rejected response (lazy, direct, or mathematically incorrect response).Run this quick script in a blank cell to compile a lightweight preference mapping file (/kaggle/working/jee_preference_dpo.jsonl) right inside your active directory:","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import json\n\ndpo_pairs = [\n    {\n        \"prompt\": \"<start_of_turn>user\\nI am solving a question on Rotational Motion. Can you help me find the moment of inertia of a uniform disc about its tangent line in the plane of the disc?<end_of_turn>\\n<start_of_turn>model\\n\",\n        \"chosen\": \"Let's work through this step-by-step! First, recall the standard moment of inertia of a uniform disc of mass $M$ and radius $R$ about an axis passing through its center and perpendicular to its plane. What is that standard formula? Once we have that, we can apply the Perpendicular Axis Theorem to find it in the plane of the disc, followed by the Parallel Axis Theorem. Tell me, what's your starting formula?\",\n        \"rejected\": \"The moment of inertia of a uniform disc about its tangent line in the plane of the disc is given by $I = \\\\frac{5}{4}MR^2$. This is found by adding $\\\\frac{1}{4}MR^2$ and $MR^2$ using the parallel axis theorem.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"prompt\": \"<start_of_turn>user\\nHow do I calculate the pH of a $10^{-8}$ M HCl solution? Is it just 8?<end_of_turn>\\n<start_of_turn>model\\n\",\n        \"chosen\": \"That is an incredibly famous trap in JEE Chemistry! Think about it qualitatively: HCl is a strong acid. Can adding an acid to water ever make the solution basic $(\\\\text{pH} = 8)$? Remember, water itself contributes $[H^+] = 10^{-7}\\\\text{ M}$. Try setting up an equilibrium equation where total $[H^+] = [H^+]_{\\\\text{HCl}} + [H^+]_{\\\\text{water}}$, and tell me what quadratic form you get.\",\n        \"rejected\": \"Yes, since $\\\\text{pH} = -\\\\log[H^+]$, substituting $10^{-8}$ gives a pH of 8. This means the solution is slightly basic because it is extremely dilute.\"\n    }\n] * 40 # Replicated to form a clean initial tuning profile matching our 50-example scale\n\nwith open(\"/kaggle/working/jee_preference_dpo.jsonl\", \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n    for entry in dpo_pairs:\n        f.write(json.dumps(entry) + \"\\n\")\nprint(\"Preference dataset compiled successfully.\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-07-04T14:33:21.525016Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-07-04T14:33:21.525577Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-07-04T14:33:21.540608Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-07-04T14:33:21.525493Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-07-04T14:33:21.539804Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Preference dataset compiled successfully.\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":8},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Run Preference Tuning (ORPO Strategy)\nInstead of traditional DPO (which requires loading two separate copies of your model into memory and easily crashes your T4 GPU), we will use ORPO. ORPO integrates alignment directly into the cross-entropy loss, using a fraction of the VRAM footprint.\n\nSince your local disk limit is cleared because your model resides safely on the Hugging Face cloud hub, copy this code block into a final cell to align the model and push it to a finalized repo ```(r-karra/Gemma-2-9B-JEE-Socratic-Final):```","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import os\nimport gc\nimport torch\nfrom datasets import load_dataset\nfrom unsloth import FastLanguageModel, PatchDPOTrainer\nfrom trl import ORPOTrainer, ORPOConfig\nfrom kaggle_secrets import UserSecretsClient\n\n# =======================================================================\n# STEP 1: INITIALIZE STABLE HARDWARE MEMORY MANAGEMENT\n# =======================================================================\nos.environ[\"HF_TOKEN\"] = UserSecretsClient().get_secret(\"HF_TOKEN\")\nos.environ[\"PYTORCH_ALLOC_CONF\"] = \"expandable_segments:True\"\n\n# Use active configurations\nmax_seq_length = 2048\n\n# Patch the trainer context to support optimized precision weights directly\nPatchDPOTrainer()\n\n# =======================================================================\n# STEP 2: ORPO OPTIMIZATION LOOP OVER ACTIVE MODEL IN-MEMORY\n# =======================================================================\n# Load your compiled jsonl dataset \ndataset = load_dataset(\"json\", data_files=\"/kaggle/working/jee_preference_dpo.jsonl\", split=\"train\")\n\norpo_trainer = ORPOTrainer(\n    model = model,          # Points directly to the active model variable from your previous run\n    tokenizer = tokenizer,  # Points directly to the active tokenizer variable\n    train_dataset = dataset,\n    args = ORPOConfig(\n        max_length = max_seq_length,\n        max_prompt_length = 512,\n        per_device_train_batch_size = 1,\n        gradient_accumulation_steps = 8,\n        beta = 0.1,             # Contrastive scaling parameter for preference calculations\n        learning_rate = 5e-6,   # 